While big manufacturers – of cars, for example – are obliged to follow new European standards set in Brussels, smaller manufacturers of niche products are just as likely to abandon Europe for more profitable markets as produce a new product range.

The new legislation comes despite a pledge by Jean-Claude Juncker, president-designate of the European Commission, to cut back on red tape by focusing the Brussels bureaucracy’s work on matters that are essential for the smooth running of European business.

Last month there was a stampede of panic-buying when a Brussels diktat outlawed powerful vacuum cleaners over 1600 watts.

A list of 30 high-wattage household devices could also be banned next spring following a draft EU report which examined ways to reduce power consumption.

These are thought to include powerful hairdryers and kettles.  

